"text": "Appart from light microscopes, scientists also use powerful electron microscopes that reveal the details of a cell structure. These instruments use a beam of electrons instead of light to produce highly magnified images, allowing us to see cell structure at the nanometre scale with remarkable clarity (a nanometre is one-billionth of a metre).\n\nEstimated size of the onion peel cell = \n\nNumber of cells along the diameter\n\nIf the estimated size of an onion peel cell is 200 $\mu$m, how much does a light microscope magnify this cell? The total magnification depends on its magnifying power of the eyepiece and the objective lens. If both the eyepiece and the objective lens have the magnifying power of 10X, then the total magnification will be 100X. This means that a cell with an estimated size of 200 $\mu$m will appear 100 times larger.\n\nThus, a microscope allows us to see very small structures clearly and is an essential tool for studying the cell structure. Over the years, scientists have improved the microscope by improving its three main features — resolution (measure of clarity), contrast (the difference in brightness between various",
